CabsOnline Part 2 - README
Student: Robert | ID: 23217839
==================================================

1. PUBLIC URL
--------------
https://lekatca1.github.io/cabsonline-part2

(Deploy with: npm run deploy)


2. TECHNOLOGY STACK
--------------------
- React 18.2
- react-leaflet 4.2.1 + Leaflet 1.9.4 (map)
- OpenStreetMap tiles (free, no API key needed)
- localStorage (demo data storage, no backend needed for GitHub Pages)
- gh-pages 6.0 (deployment)
- CSS (plain, no extra libraries)


3. HOW TO RUN LOCALLY
----------------------
Requirements: Node.js 16+, npm

Steps:
  1. Unzip the project folder
  2. Open terminal in the project folder
  3. Run: npm install
  4. Run: npm start
  5. Open http://localhost:3000 in your browser

To build for production:
  npm run build

To deploy to GitHub Pages:
  npm run deploy


4. FEATURES
------------

Feature 1 – Book a Taxi (tab: "Book a Taxi")
  Extends Part 1 booking.html into React.
  - All the same fields: cname, phone, unumber, snumber, stname, sbname, dsbname, date, time
  - Client-side validation (required fields, phone format, date not in past)
  - Generates BRN in format BRN00001, BRN00002, etc.
  - Shows confirmation with booking reference number, pickup date and time
  - Stores booking in localStorage (demo storage)

Feature 2 – Booking Status Tracker (tab: "Track Booking")
  Customers can check the status of their booking.
  - Enter a BRN (e.g. BRN00001) to look up their booking
  - Shows status progress bar: unassigned → assigned → completed
  - Displays all booking details in a table

Feature 3 – Fare Estimator (tab: "Fare Estimator")
  Estimates the fare before booking.
  - Select pickup and destination from Auckland suburb list
  - Enter pickup time to check for night surcharge (10pm–6am = +20%)
  - Shows base fare, distance charge, and total estimate
  - Shows typical min/max fare range

Feature 4 – Driver Map View (tab: "Driver Map")
  Shows mock taxi driver locations on an interactive map.
  - Uses Leaflet + OpenStreetMap (no API key needed)
  - Green dots = online drivers, grey = offline
  - Click a marker to see driver name, car, plate, area
  - Filter drivers by online/offline status
  - Driver card list below the map


5. TESTING INSTRUCTIONS
------------------------

Example booking flow:
  1. Go to "Book a Taxi" tab
  2. Fill in: Name=John Smith, Phone=0211234567, Street No=1, Street=Queen St
  3. Leave date/time as default (current)
  4. Click "Book Now"
  5. Note your BRN (e.g. BRN00001)

Track a booking:
  1. Go to "Track Booking" tab
  2. Enter BRN00001 (or whatever BRN you received)
  3. Click Search to see details and status

Fare estimate:
  1. Go to "Fare Estimator" tab
  2. Pick "Auckland CBD" as pickup, "Albany" as destination
  3. Try 23:00 as time to see night surcharge applied
  4. Click "Estimate Fare"

Driver map:
  1. Go to "Driver Map" tab
  2. Click on green/grey dots to see driver info
  3. Use online/offline filter buttons

History:
  1. Go to "History" tab to see all bookings made this session

Sample driver IDs: D001, D002, D003, D004, D005, D006


6. LIMITATIONS / KNOWN ISSUES
-------------------------------
- Data is stored in localStorage only — it resets if the browser clears storage
- Fare estimates are approximate (based on fixed suburb distances, not real GPS routing)
- Driver locations are simulated (mock data, not real-time GPS)
- No authentication — same as Part 1 (not required by assignment)
- The "assigned" and "completed" status cannot be set from the customer side
  (admin would need to update status — this is a demo limitation)


7. REFLECTION ON AI-SUPPORTED DEVELOPMENT
-------------------------------------------
AI assistance (Claude) was used to help scaffold the React component structure,
suggest appropriate Leaflet setup for fixing default marker icons in React,
and advise on how to structure localStorage as a demo replacement for a PHP backend
on GitHub Pages. The core logic (validation rules, BRN format, field names) was
taken directly from the Part 1 specification and existing code to ensure consistency.

The AI helped speed up repetitive boilerplate (CSS styling, form wiring) while the
student made design decisions about feature selection, data structure, and UX flow.
